Morning in Isla Barba Azul Cerrado, afternoon in vehicle river edge and savanna of Barba Azul North.--Blue-throated Macaw - around 35----Copied notes for ebird lists from 16-20 September 2018--Four days at Barba Azul Nature Reserve by Asociacion Armonia as an International Conservation Fund of Canada (ICFC) visiting trip. Birdwatching the area with Anne Lambert, Tom Welch, Roy Smith and Minnie Poon. I spent a week in Barba Azul in July so interesting to compare movements.  ----Area still fairly dry, but with a few cold front rains. This year had many cold fronts. Rained on 17SEP18 morning, smoky before the rain, after hazy clouds not great light for photography. Rainy season sky is very clear with variation on cumulus clouds. ----The Blue-throated Macaws were only seen around Isla Barba Azul where there appeared to be around 42 individuals. Heard and seen flying throughout the day, breaking up into smaller groups. They left for the roosting site much earlier- with individuals leaving at 17:15 and the majority gone by 17:30. None around at 18:00, whereas in July the majority of birds were leaving at this time. --Blue-and-Yellow Macaw were rare seeing a few pair each day. No real roosting movement this time. ----Certain very common birds in July were almost completely absent like Orinoco Goose (only saw two entire period), the two Whistling Ducks, great Egret.  ----Forest birds singing and responding well to PLBK- but Savanna birds are not singing on territory- other than Pampa Wren. Probably savanna birds will be breeding in November.----Common Cerrado tree in fruit being eaten by many species- very evident. Cerrado was very low on austral migrant flycatchers. Saw Boreal Swallow in a massive group in the rain, another group 200 next day- and dispersed ind the next. No Nacundas, terns or skimmers. ----Days are clearly hotter than July. Both Potoos are singing. Chachlaca still only live at Barba Azul island east.

Sunrise at about 6:09, crossed lake to grasslands on north west side of Barba Azul Island long western boundary of reserve (Barba Azul Norte). Walked alongside marshes to grasslands, then a little within forest of Barba Azul Island on way back. Saw Marsh Deer (female), capybara herd, Pampas Deer (male), and heard 2 Maned Wolf. Dipped on Streamer-tailed Tyrant.
SPECIES COMMENTS: at least 3 birds, maybe 4. Last burned in 2012. dry season. 8 am in the morning.

TRIP COMMENTS: We birded the upper areas of the park. Habitat: expansive grasslands with some shrubby trees. Narrow stream beds support a dense, elfin gallery woodland. Thick, viney ferns are found in the gallery wood and around wet areas. The grassland is in differing stages of succession according to how recently it was burned. Windy.
Mostly sunny, afternoon rainshower on the plateau.  A fantastic morning drive on the high plateau.
Mostly sunny, afternoon rainshower on the plateau.  A fantastic morning drive on the high plateau, after the park opened at 08:00.

with guide Marcelo Padua and local ranger Renato, on trip with Rita, Dan Singer, Chris Tenney. Today we first visited ''lagoon de capybara'' in hopes for large mammals (none) but we did see 2 Tapir and a Maned Wolf on our predawn drive to park [not on this checklist]. Then an hour in Formosa river forest and an early picnic lunch at hdqs., a rest, and then a long drive to NW quandrant of park, where we visited an isolated marsh (used as a wallow by White-lipped Peccaries; photos) and returned through the park, covering lots of good grassland habitat by van. We then left park and went to a farm reserve to the south, met up with Braulio Carlos & clients, and walked out to see Giant Anteater [see separate checklist for that]
Mostly cloudy, breezy, and cool to warm. Drove perimeter road to park guard housing then on to bridge and trail into flooded forest before returning to bus along perimeter road.

with Jim & Sue Graham, David & Sue Cohen. Drove as far as the turnoff on the right to Rolinhos. A large portion of the upper park had been burned 3 weeks prior, and the park had only re-opened the day prior to our visit. Weather clear with some clouds, relatively cool and breezy.----Great sightings of a huge Six-banded Armadillo, two Giant Anteaters (one distant), and a fabulous Maned Wolf sighting not far from the Curral de Pedra to cap off a wonderful day.

with Rolph Davis. We left Chapadão do Céu after 05h30 breakfast. Today we headed for the Mirante do Avoador in the north-central range of the park, birding the campo limpo on the upper plateau en route. We didn't get to the Mirante until nearly 11 AM. Birding was pretty good, and there was a lot to look at in the areas which had been recently burned to create firebreaks. Back to town for lunch, then we returned to the hotel to rest until 15h30. We returned to the park in the afternoon, spending an unproductive afternoon driving tracks in the southwest corner of the park around the Trilha da Gloria. We were unsuccessful in the full moon looking for White-winged Nightjar along the landing strip.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Abundant in campo limpo atop the plateau en route to Avoador, but also elsewhere in the park.

Na companhia dos amigos Adilson Marques, Lindolfo Souto e sua esposa. Guiados pelo amigo Geiser Trivelato.

Observações sistemáticas realizadas estritamente no interior do PN das Emas, durante o período de 27/11 até 01/12/2015. Percorremos principalmente as áreas de campo sujo e cerrado strictu sensu, além da mata de galeria ao longo do Rio Formoso e Jacuba. Acompanhado, na unidade, pelo guia Nélio Carrijo.----Mamíferos observados - Cerdocyon thous, Lycalopex vetulus, Chrysocyon brachyurus, Myrmecophaga tridactyla, Tapirus terrestris, Didelphis albiventris, Tayassu tajacu, Ozotocerus bezoarticus, Blastocerus dichotomus, Mazama gouazoubira, Cebus libidinosus, Callithrix penicillata.
